# Code Quality & Best Practices

## Core Development Principles

### Code Writing Standards
- Follow the user's requirements carefully & to the letter
- First think step-by-step - describe your plan in pseudocode, written out in great detail
- Always write correct, best practice, DRY principle (Don't Repeat Yourself), bug-free, fully functional code
- Focus on readability over performance optimization
- Fully implement all requested functionality
- Leave NO todos, placeholders, or missing pieces
- Ensure code is complete and thoroughly verified
- Include all required imports and ensure proper naming of key components

### Communication Principles
- Be concise and minimize unnecessary prose
- If uncertain about the correct answer, say so explicitly
- If you don't know the answer, say so instead of guessing
- Provide nuanced, thoughtful answers with careful reasoning

## Code Structure & Organization

### File Organization
- Use descriptive file and folder names
- Group related functionality together
- Follow consistent naming conventions
- Separate concerns appropriately

### Function & Variable Naming
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Use camelCase for variables and functions
- Use PascalCase for components and classes
- Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants

```typescript
// Good: Descriptive naming
const calculateTotalPrice = (items: CartItem[]) => { ... };
const isUserAuthenticated = () => { ... };
const MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS = 3;

// Bad: Unclear naming
const calc = (arr: any[]) => { ... };
const check = () => { ... };
const x = 3;
```

### Function Design
- Use arrow functions with const declarations
- Keep functions small and focused (single responsibility)
- Use early returns to reduce nesting
- Define proper TypeScript types for parameters and return values

```typescript
// Good: Well-structured function
const processUserData = (userData: UserData | null): ProcessedUser | null => {
  if (!userData) {
    return null; // Early return
  }

  if (!userData.isValid) {
    return null; // Early return
  }

  return {
    id: userData.id,
    name: userData.name.trim(),
    email: userData.email.toLowerCase(),
  };
};
```

## Error Handling

### Comprehensive Error Management
- Always handle potential errors gracefully
- Provide meaningful error messages to users
- Use try-catch blocks for async operations
- Implement proper error boundaries in React

```typescript
// Good: Proper error handling
const fetchUserData = async (userId: string): Promise<User | null> => {
  try {
    const response = await api.get(`/users/${userId}`);
    return response.data;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Failed to fetch user data:', error);
    // Don't throw, return null and handle gracefully
    return null;
  }
};
```

### Form Validation
- Validate inputs on both client and server
- Provide clear, actionable error messages
- Use proper validation libraries (Zod, Yup)

## Performance Considerations

### React Performance
- Use React.memo for components with stable props
- Implement proper dependency arrays in useEffect
- Use useCallback for event handlers passed as props
- Use useMemo for expensive calculations

```typescript
// Good: Optimized component
const ExpensiveComponent = React.memo(({ data, onUpdate }: Props) => {
  const processedData = useMemo(() => {
    return data.map(item => ({ ...item, processed: true }));
  }, [data]);

  const handleUpdate = useCallback((id: string) => {
    onUpdate(id);
  }, [onUpdate]);

  return (
    <div>
      {processedData.map(item => (
        <Item key={item.id} data={item} onUpdate={handleUpdate} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
});
```

## Testing & Validation

### Code Verification
- Test all code paths and edge cases
- Verify error states and loading states
- Ensure proper TypeScript typing
- Test accessibility with keyboard navigation

### Input Validation
- Never trust user input
- Sanitize and validate all inputs
- Use schema validation for forms
- Implement proper authentication checks

## Documentation & Comments

### Code Documentation
- Write self-documenting code with clear names
- Add comments only when necessary to explain "why," not "what"
- Document complex business logic
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes

```typescript
// Good: Meaningful comment explaining business logic
const calculateDiscountPrice = (price: number, userTier: UserTier): number => {
  // Premium users get 15% discount, regular users get 5%
  // This aligns with the marketing promotion strategy
  const discountRate = userTier === 'premium' ? 0.15 : 0.05;
  return price * (1 - discountRate);
};
```

## Security Best Practices

### Data Protection
- Never expose sensitive data in client-side code
- Sanitize user inputs to prevent XSS
- Use proper authentication and authorization
- Validate data on both client and server sides

### API Security
- Use proper HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
- Implement rate limiting
- Validate API inputs
- Use HTTPS for all communications

## Import & Dependency Management

### Import Organization
- Group imports logically (external libraries, internal modules, types)
- Use absolute imports with path aliases (@/)
- Import only what you need to reduce bundle size

```typescript
// Good: Organized imports
import React, { useState, useCallback } from 'react';
import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';

import { Button } from '@/components/ui/button';
import { UserService } from '@/services/user';
import { validateEmail } from '@/utils/validation';

import type { User } from '@/types/user';
import type { FormErrors } from '@/types/forms';
```

### Dependency Management
- Keep dependencies up to date
- Use exact versions for critical dependencies
- Remove unused dependencies regularly
- Prefer established, well-maintained packages

## Code Review Checklist

### Before Submitting Code
- [ ] All functionality is fully implemented
- [ ] No TODOs or placeholders remain
- [ ] Error handling is comprehensive
- [ ] TypeScript types are properly defined
- [ ] Code follows naming conventions
- [ ] Accessibility requirements are met
- [ ] Performance optimizations are applied where needed
- [ ] Code is well-documented where necessary
- [ ] All imports are organized and necessary
